20 Feb 2026

Problem 1 (CMO 2013 P1)

Determine all polynomials P(x) with real coefficients such that

(x+1)P(x-1)-(x-1)P(x) is constant


----------------------------------------
(TeX Solution)
-----------
Storage
Pogres
Sol set P(x)=c
dam bro

Let k be the constant such that
(x+1)P(x-1)-(x-1)P(x)=k

When x=1, P(0)=k/2
When x=0, P(-1)=k/2
Let Q(x) = P(x)-k/2 which has roots 0 and -1
Q(x) = R(x)x(x+1)
(x+1)(R(x-1)(x-1)x+k/2)-(x-1)(R(x)x(x+1)+k/2)=k
(x+1)R(x-1)(x-1)x-(x-1)R(x)x(x+1)=0
x(x-1)(x+1)(R(x-1)-R(x))=0
so R(x-1)=R(x)
Denote a polynomial S(x)=R(x)-R(0), S(x) has infinite roots, so it is the 0 polynomial.
Therefore R(x) is constant for all x, let R(x)=c_1
P(x)=c_1*x*(x+1)+k/2
Substituting to the original question,
(x+1)(c_1*x*(x-1)+k/2)-(x-1)(c_1*x*(x+1)+k/2)=k
(x+1)x(x-1)c_1-(x-1)x(x+1)c_1=0 which works for all c_1,k.
P(x) = c_1*x*(x+1)+c works where c_1,c is in R.
------------------
Writeup
Claim that all polynomials in the form of P(x)=c_1*x*(x+1)+c works for any choice of reals c and c_1.
Let k be the constant such that
(x+1)P(x-1)-(x-1)P(x)=k, then realize that P(x)=c_1*x*(x+1)+k/2 is a solution.
Substituting to the original question,
(x+1)(c_1*x*(x-1)+k/2)-(x-1)(c_1*x*(x+1)+k/2)=k
(x+1)x(x-1)c_1-(x-1)x(x+1)c_1=0 which works for all c_1,k.
P(x) = c_1*x*(x+1)+c works where c_1,c is in R.

When x=1, P(0)=k/2
When x=0, P(-1)=k/2
